notes.note:
Hello, thanks for sending that over. Trust me, I do that all the time too! Normally we would ask for an actual receipt but in light of the issues with the debit system, we can move forward with the screen shot. There are a couple things you should be aware of in regards to the payout for reimbursement amount listed below. Our Mitchell Labour Guide calls for 3.2 hours for the replacement of the radiator, compared to the 4 hours Dodge quoted on the estimate. We can only pay out the maximum allowable labour listed on our Labour Guide. Additionally, we pay out a maximum of $130/h, so this will reflect in the labour portion of the reimbursement payout break down. Lastly, just so that you are aware, we do not cover fluids, or the maintenance (oil change) performed on the truck, so this will account for a difference between the repair bill you paid for and the reimbursement amount authorized below. The payout is as follows:

Parts-$755.00
Labour-$416.00 (3.2 hours x $130/h)
Deductible-$0
Tax-$175.36
Authorization-DQW38ACMR3

Total reimbursement payout - $1346.36

This claim will now be closed and passed over to the accounts payable department who will write you a reimbursement cheque in the amount of $1346.36 and mail it to the address that is listed on the invoice which you have confirmed is the correct current mailing address.

Enjoy the rest of your day!

Cheers,

Matthew Puls
Claims Adjuster

notes.note:
Customer appealed my decision. I replied:
 Thanks for your email.
I've reviewed your file and the quote that was submitted by Ron MacGillivray GM.
The quote show 3 failures:
1-TPM (Tire pressure monitor) light on. 
Wiring repair. Neither the TPM nor the wring are covered.
2- Encoder motor shorted.
The 4 wheel drive encoder motor is not listed as a covered component and is not an internal part. 
3-Trailer brake control module.
While all ECU's are covered, the contract excludes failure as a result of corrosion. Please see "Events That Are Not Covered By This Warranty Contract", Section 20 - "20. any Vehicle damage due to wear and tear, corrosion, rust, or other gradual loss or reduction of function;
There is no mention of a keyless entry problem on the quote.
I've attached a copy of the quote submitted by Ron MacGillivray.
I trust this explains our position. If you have any further questions, please feel free to contact me.

Sincerely,

A.H.

notes.content: Rec'd quote from Selkirk Chrysler for replacement of both front upper ball joints, passenger side outer tie rod and driver's side cv axle. M.P.

notes.note:
Great, thank you for sending that over. The only reason I asked is because the km's at the contract start date were the same km's you had listed on the estimate as the in km's for this service. 
As we discussed earlier over the phone, the customer is covered for the replacement of both front upper control arms, and the passenger side front outer tie rod end. Unfortunately they are not covered for the replacement of the driver's side axle as you stated that it requires replacement due to the boot being split. 

Please be advised, listed on the estimate, you requested 1.8 hours per side for the replacement of the upper control arms. Mitchell lists 1.0 hour per side, but I have adjusted it to 1.4 hours per side to meet half way, plus the additional 0.2 for the right side front outer tie rod end for a combined labour total of 3.0 hours.
As you may already be aware of, the customer is responsible for any diagnostic fees, shop supplies, labour overages (we pay out $130/h, your shop rate is $155/h), and the alignment, as well as a $100 deductible. 

The payout is as follows:

Parts-$218.40
Labour-$390.00 (3.0 hours x $130/h)
Deductible-$100.00

notes.content:
Great, thank you for sending that over. The only reason I asked is because the km's at the contract start date were the same km's you had listed on the estimate as the in km's for this service.
As we discussed earlier over the phone, the customer is covered for the replacement of both front upper control arms, and the passenger side front outer tie rod end. Unfortunately they are not covered for the replacement of the driver's side axle as you stated that it requires replacement due to the boot being split.

Please be advised, listed on the estimate, you requested 1.8 hours per side for the replacement of the upper control arms. Mitchell lists 1.0 hour per side, but I have adjusted it to 1.4 hours per side to meet half way, plus the additional 0.2 for the right side front outer tie rod end for a combined labour total of 3.0 hours.
As you may already be aware of, the customer is responsible for any diagnostic fees, shop supplies, labour overages (we pay out $130/h, your shop rate is $155/h), and the alignment, as well as a $100 deductible.
